[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.140]   This is a Kell blog post from July 17, 2006 titled Hope and Agility, The Revlon Test.
[00:00:06.140 --> 00:00:10.940]   Charles Rebsen, the founder of Revlon, was once quoted (see page 7) as saying,
[00:00:10.940 --> 00:00:15.280]   "In the factory Revlon manufactures cosmetics, but in the store we sell hope."
[00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:18.300]   While his customers may not have appreciated this characterization,
[00:00:18.300 --> 00:00:22.660]   I have always remembered it as a pithy quote that dramatizes the ultimate benefit of a product.
[00:00:22.660 --> 00:00:26.980]   In fact, I think it's important that every CEO be able to answer the following question,
[00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:29.540]   "If Revlon sells hope, then what do we sell?"
[00:00:29.540 --> 00:00:31.340]   I call this the Revlon Test.
[00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:32.460]   And there's a catch.
