[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.280]   This is a Kill Blod post from July 24, 2006 titled "Thoughts on Blink". I just got back
[00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:09.600]   from vacation in France. Showing great restraint, I will resist the temptation to rant about the
[00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:14.320]   continuing lack of customer service there. Note, avoid renting from Hertz in France when possible,
[00:00:14.320 --> 00:00:19.040]   and most certainly at CDG. Instead, I'll talk about the book on read while flying,
[00:00:19.040 --> 00:00:22.560]   Blink by Malcolm Gladwell, also author of The Tipping Point.
[00:00:22.560 --> 00:00:26.400]   I was a big fan of The Tipping Point and thus approached Blink with the same trepidation with
[00:00:26.400 --> 00:00:31.840]   when it approaches any sequel, E.G.D. Hard 2. This, in fact, explains why it took me over a
[00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:36.560]   year to get around to reading it. Blink is all about the power of our unconscious mind.
[00:00:36.560 --> 00:00:40.240]   Gladwell details numerous rather stunning experiments that show our unconscious mind
[00:00:40.240 --> 00:00:45.680]   has significant, generally unknown and untapped powers. Next, when pulling cards from two decks,
[00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:49.760]   when one deck is loaded with bad cards, people will show physical stress signs when drawing
[00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:53.600]   from the loaded deck long before they actually realize that it is loaded with bad cards.
[00:00:53.600 --> 00:00:57.360]   Next, experts showing just three minutes of a newly married couple discussing a
[00:00:57.360 --> 00:01:02.080]   controversial topic can predict with 80 plus plus accuracy whether they will remain married in 10
[00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:07.200]   years. Next, experts showing just a few minutes of a doctor interacting with a patient can predict
[00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:10.640]   with high accuracy, which doctors will be sued more often than others.
[00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:17.680]   Next, priming. People by lacing words of a certain genre, E.G., old words, polite words into a simple
[00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.280]   English quiz, biases their subsequent behavior. For example, biasing a test with old words will
[00:01:23.280 --> 00:01:28.160]   make them walk more slowly when leaving the exam. Eight polite words will cause them to wait longer,
[00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:32.640]   in his example, up to the maximum 10 minutes before interrupting a conversation so they can leave.
[00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:37.200]   Next, students shown just a few seconds of a professor teaching a class will rate him
[00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:41.680]   her virtually the same as students who take a semester-long class. It is worth reading the
[00:01:41.680 --> 00:01:45.840]   book to learn about these studies alone, but having spent most of my career in information
[00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:50.480]   technology, it was the sections related to information overload and information processing
[00:01:50.480 --> 00:01:55.200]   that most interested me. Those of us in IT have an implicit assumption that more information is
[00:01:55.200 --> 00:02:00.000]   better. Just look at some of the taglines used by BI vendors over the years. Next,
[00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:04.720]   Cognos – better decisions every day. Next, SAS – the power to know.
[00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:09.920]   Next, Informatica – now you know. In fact, neither Cognos nor SAS nor anyone
[00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:15.120]   else in the category sells software that explicitly addresses either knowledge or decision-making.
[00:02:15.120 --> 00:02:20.000]   They sell software that produces information. The logic chain of the marketing is, more information
[00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.280]   better decisions. But is it so? Blink suggests not. Gladwell details a war game done by the army
[00:02:25.280 --> 00:02:29.520]   where an abundance of information caused commanders to miss a sneak attack. He starts the book with
[00:02:29.520 --> 00:02:33.840]   the case of a fake statue purchased by the Getty Museum where, despite cut reactions from experts
[00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:38.800]   that something was wrong (Ogagi, one expert said it looked too fresh), a pile of detailed reports
[00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:43.920]   (Ogagi, mineral aging, rock-saurus style) managed to convince the experts to disregard their instincts
[00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:48.080]   and believe the statue was legitimate. He goes further to show how the human body reacts to
[00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:52.960]   moments of high stress with a selective autism, whereby we shut down many information-gathering
[00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:56.720]   channels and focus only on the immediate problem by getting testimony from police
[00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:01.440]   officers involved in shootings. In a crisis, it seems, less information is better than more.
[00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:06.240]   My problem with the book is that it seems to say, "Next, you have this amazing set of
[00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.160]   subconscious abilities that you didn't know you had. Next, but you shouldn't use them because
[00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:13.920]   you'd then be prejudicial. You might vote for Warren Harding because he looked presidential,
[00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:17.360]   or you might reject a female trombonist because you're unconsciously wired to believe it's a
[00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:21.760]   male instrument. If you want to conduct fair orchestra tryouts, then do them blind, behind a
[00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:26.240]   screen. It wasn't clear what you were supposed to do to vote correctly. So I found the book to end
[00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:29.760]   rather abruptly, without ever attempting to prescribe how one should apply this newfound
[00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:34.640]   knowledge. Since Gladwell doesn't do so, I'll take my own swag at it. Next, be aware that you
[00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:39.760]   have these powers. Next, be aware when you overrule them. Don't let piles of data completely drown
[00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:44.800]   out a gut instinct. Know that in certain situations, response speed and an expert's gut instinct beat
[00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:49.440]   piles of data and analysis. Next, be aware that these powers are fickle and fragile. They may be
[00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:53.840]   as misprogrammed in your head as an irrational bias against female trombonists. Critical thank
[00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:58.080]   your gut reactions. To make the best decisions, try to find the right way to combine data-driven
[00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:02.560]   and gut-instinct decisions. Try to find the right way to combine data-driven and gut-instinct
[00:04:02.560 --> 00:04:07.120]   decision-making. For other interesting books on decision-making, check out Decision Traps,
[00:04:07.120 --> 00:04:11.760]   The Classic, Winning Decisions, The Sequel Rewrite, which title recast in a positive
[00:04:11.760 --> 00:04:15.920]   light, or Smart Choices. The New York Times review of Blink can be found here.
