[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.640]   This is a Kellblad post from August 12, 2006 titled Parallel Evolution, ECM, and BI. With all
[00:00:06.640 --> 00:00:10.720]   the M&A activity of late in the ECM space, I thought it would be a good time to do some
[00:00:10.720 --> 00:00:15.600]   comparison between the ECM and the BI markets. Recall that, prior to joining MarkLogic,
[00:00:15.600 --> 00:00:20.480]   the content world, I spent nearly a decade in Business Intelligence, or BI, the data world.
[00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:24.400]   Since few people have spent a lot of time on both sides of the data content divide,
[00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:29.760]   I think I can bring an interesting perspective. Both the BI and ECM spaces grew up as applications
[00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:36.800]   tools on top of relational databases, or DBMSs. ECM has its roots in document management. BI has
[00:00:36.800 --> 00:00:41.920]   its roots in ad hoc query and reporting. Both started as cottage industries with many specialized
[00:00:41.920 --> 00:00:46.400]   vendors serving many subcategories of what has converged today to become a broader, more general
[00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:52.640]   market. For example, in BI, Cognos specialized in online analytic processing (OWAPAP),
[00:00:52.640 --> 00:00:58.240]   business objects specialized in ad hoc query and reporting (QNR), and crystal reports specialized
[00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:04.640]   in enterprise reporting (ER). In ECM, Documentum specialized in document management, Interwoven
[00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:10.320]   specialized in web content management, and FileNet specialized in imaging. As time passed and as
[00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:14.240]   shakeouts occurred in the subcategories, the subcategory leaders naturally decided to move
[00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:19.040]   into adjacent subcategories. Often this starts out as product development, some of which succeeds and
[00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:23.760]   much of which fails. Sometimes it starts out as third-party licensing. Usually it ends with an
[00:01:23.760 --> 00:01:28.160]   M&A frenzy because there are actually two things going on. First, each vendor is watching the
[00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:33.680]   progress of the others and getting the complete suite product line. In BI, the complete suite is
[00:01:33.680 --> 00:01:40.240]   ETL, QNR, OLAP, ER, planning, budgeting, data profiling quality, and analytic applications.
[00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:45.600]   In ECM, the complete suite is document management, web content management, imaging,
[00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:51.200]   records management, workflow, and digital asset management. See this Gilbane report dated 2004 for
[00:01:51.200 --> 00:01:55.760]   more. Second, each vendor is watching the relative size of the other vendors in this process.
[00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:59.760]   No one wants to be left behind in the race for scale, or critical mass.
[00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:04.720]   The problem with the enterprise suite idesation strategy is that it usually results in worst of
[00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:09.920]   breed product lines. In reality, the leaders in each of the N-subcategories buy the losers in the
[00:02:09.920 --> 00:02:16.080]   other N1.think, business objects buying ACTA or SRC, Cognos buying decision stream, or Hyperion
[00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:20.480]   buying Brio long past its sell-by date. Sure, there are sometimes exceptions where leaders buy
[00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:26.080]   leaders, EEG, EMC Documentum buying Captiva or business objects buying Crystal. But the typical
[00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:31.360]   outcome of this phase of market evolution is… Next, highly uneven product lines with respect
[00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:35.920]   to product strength quality. Next, little or no product integration across the suite were fully
