[00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.600]   This is a Kell blog post from August 16th, 2006 titled "You Are What You Search".
[00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:10.000]   Just a quick post to this very interesting article on Slate.com by Paul Boughton that I found here
[00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.040]   on Slashdot. Using the tools at Splunk.com and the search history records on 650k members that
[00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:19.840]   were released and subsequently retracted by AOL, Boughton makes a taxonomy of seven different types
[00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.720]   of internet search users. Next, the Pornhound next, the Manhunter next, the Shopper next,
[00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:29.600]   the Obsessive next, the Omnivore next, the Omnivore next, the Newbie next, the Basket case,
[00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:33.920]   the Depth of the released data is a little scary. You can see searches in chronological order in the
[00:00:33.920 --> 00:00:37.520]   exact search terms used dot com by Paul Boughton makes a taxonomy of seven different types of
[00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:42.080]   internet search users. For a concrete lesson on internet privacy, click here to see the search
[00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:47.680]   history for AOL user 67268. From the article, when John Vettel called internet search logs
[00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:52.560]   humanity's database of intentions, he wasn't far off the mark indeed. This audio version was created
[00:00:52.560 --> 00:00:55.200]   by Grant Duncan and AI with permission from Dave.
